#welcome!
this tutorial explains how to style your slides with layout positioning.

click on the **play button** ![](playbutton.svg) to begin the presentation.

and remember: you can always hit `escape` to look up the code structure of the slide, explore the menus and play around with the content.

---
## data and blocks

slidenotes reads your data and creates blocks out of it. 
then it tries to find the best solution how to evenly position these blocks on the slide.
this works well in most of the use cases and therefore makes writing slidenotes really fast. 

but sometimes you want more control. 

so we have thought about how we could implement extra options into the text editor without making it more complicated. and we came up with a tool set which we hope you'll love ➡︎

---
## introducing layout blocks

the first tool to manage easy and fast positioning is the layout block. 

you can look at it as a container, placing all the elements inside. so all you need to do is enclose your content with it.

if you want to layout elements that are already written on your slide, you can:

1. mark the code with your cursor
2. click on the **toolbar button** ![](toolbar.svg) 
3. and select **+++layout+++**

---
## layout blocks that go left

+++layout:left
one thing we can tell our new layout block to do, is to go and sit left:
1. click anywhere inside your new layout block container
2. click on the **layout context menu** ![](context-menu_layout.svg) that shows up at the beginning of your line
3. select **left**
*optional*
another way to do this, is to add the missing piece of code by hand, which is nothing more than the word ~:left~ put right next to the word ~+++layout~ in the very first line of your block.
+++

+++code:none
 +++layout:left
 content of the left layout block
 +++
+++

whenever a left layout block like such appears in your code, the slide will start to split into two parts: left and everything apart from left, which is—well—right.

in fact you are looking at said right side just now: everything left on this slide was put into a left layout block. the rest of the code elements following this block (like these very words) have no layout defining container around them and therefore sit right here.
makes sense?
wonderful! feel free to jump to the [next step](#slide7).
left? right! what!?
we know this can sound confusing at first, so let's dive a little deeper with a an easy approach ➡︎


---------
## follow the content as it gets written

this paragraph right here is the first one on this slide.
as it has no layout block wrapped around its text, it's been placed in the middle and has all the space for itself.
but:

+++layout:left
this paragraph is the third element on this slide, but the first one to show up within a layout block container. 
it says: ~+++layout:left~
so from now on the slide will be divided into parts. one of which is left because this paragraphs layout block explicitly asked for it. 
so the wish came true: it is sitting just beneath the quote, but on the left side of the slide.
+++

this fourth paragraph is just like the very first one. 
it shows no layout block or container whatsoever. 
yet it isn't placed in the center but on the right. 
why? because of a chronological difference: 
while the first paragraph appeared in times when there were still no layout blocks around, this one here showed up at a time when the slide was already divided. so there's just no centered space anymore. only the left and the other part.
and because this paragraph does not wish to be sent to the left, it gets sent to the other part. here. on the right side.

----
## layout blocks that go right

as you might have guessed, the right layout block isn't exactly a whole other story than the left layout block. in fact it's just the same logic but this time on the other side of the slide.

so let's see what happens when we:

- either add the word ~:right~ to the first line of our layout block
- or click on **right** in the **layout context menu** ![](context-menu_layout.svg) 

+++layout:right
everything in this layout block now sits on the right side of the slide.
+++code
 +++layout:right
 content of the right layout block
 +++
+++
+++

not really a surprise.

## the inline layout block

+++layout:left
slidenote offers a third block called ~layout:inline~.

in contrast to the left and right layout block, it does not take its content as is and shift it to a specific place on the slide.

it rather spreads its content in blocks along the whole width of a slide.

to do so, it reads its content looking for connected elements.

then it takes these different elements and splits them up along the width of the slide.
which means, whenever possible, it puts them in line right next to each other.

let's go and check out how that looks ➡︎
+++

--------
## the inline layout block in action

+++layout:inline
the first two lines inside this block form its first connected element.

the second element is put right beside.

and so is the third one.
+++

+++code:none
 +++layout:inline
 the first two lines inside this block form its first connected element.

 the second element is put right beside.

 and so is the third one.
 +++
+++

all the elements you place after the inline layout block keep on behaving normally.

-----

## background images for layout blocks

+++layout:left
there are many types of elements you can put inside layout blocks, images just being one of them. 

what makes images special though, is their double purpose:
as part of the layout blocks content—or as its background.

all you have to do to set an image as the background of your layout block, is to put the image tag in its very first line and then leave one line empty.

let's check out the results ➡︎
+++

+++layout:right
+++code
 +++layout:left
 ![](background image name)

 this image fills the layout block 
 while this text sits inside 
 +++
+++

+++code
 +++layout:right

 ![](image name)
 this image sits inside the layout block, 
 subtitled with this text
 +++
+++

+++

## the hidden block

last but not least, we want to introduce you to the hidden block.
it solves the following problem:
let's say you want to show various elements together on one slide, but reveal them separately—one after the other.
this slide is a great example, because the prominent white space in the middle contains a secret!

+++layout:inline
this is a slide with a hidden block.
there is someone hiding 
between these lines of text ...

+++hidden
##gotcha!
![](panda)
it's this little guy! 
let's find out how he did this ➡︎
+++

... and this text here on the right.
press `right` to find out who!
+++


---
## the hidden blocks code

+++layout:left
to have an element hiding on your slide, 
you have to put it in the hidden layout container:
it starts with the code ~+++hidden~ and ends with ~+++~.
if you don't feel like writing the hidden code by hand, 
you can select it from the **toolbar** ![](toolbar.svg).
+++hidden
by the way: 
if you hide more than one element on a slide, they'll be revealed with every step in your presentation, depending on their order inside the slides code.
+++
+++

+++layout:right
+++code
 this text will be visible when you open the slide
 +++hidden
 this text is hidden 
 and will show up when you jump to the next slide
 +++
+++
+++hidden
one 
+++
+++hidden
after the other
+++
+++hidden
while first
+++
+++hidden
comes first.
+++
+++

---
## the hidden blocks placement: dos

+++layout:inline
you can hide any element on your slide.
even if it's part of a layout block.
just nest the element inside the hidden container,
then nest this container into the layouting one.

+++code:none
 +++layout:left
 text that is shown on the left side of the slide
 +++hidden
 text that is hidden on the left side of the slide
 +++
 +++
+++
+++

+++layout:inline

![](not hiding cat 1)
not hiding inside this ~layout:inline~ block

![](not hiding cat 2)
not bothering to hide inside here either

+++hidden
![](hiding cat)
hiding inside this ~layout:inline~ block
+++
+++


----
## the hidden blocks placement: don'ts

+++layout:left
yet there's something you shouldn't do 
when hiding stuff on your slide.
and that's trying to hide only parts of an element.

here's why:
elements only work as such 
because their code is written in a certain way. 
often, it's the combination of lines 
that tells slidenote what's what.

so, when you want to hide something,
you need the code lines ~+++hidden~ and ~+++~.
this inevitably leads to a break between the lines,
which messes up the code of the elements. 
+++

+++layout:right
for example:
a line of text will only be transformed into an images subtitle, if it sits in the line directly beneath the image tag.

+++code:none
 ![](image name)
 text for image subtitle
+++

hiding only the subtitle won't work out.

+++code:none
 ![](image name)
 +++ hidden
 text for image subtitle 
 now reads as normal text
 because it doesn't sit 
 in the line beneeth the image tag
 +++
+++
+++
